bug.short_desc: Verrryyyyyy long time for generator to process a mixin with large JavaScript map

long_desc.thetext:
The attached file takes nearly five minutes for the generator to process.
Thomas believes it may have something to do with the embedded data URLs. (Those are ordinary strings here, though, and need not be specially processed.)

Created attachment 1000 File that causes the problem.
I have zipped the file as it was 18k too large to attach, otherwise.

I've commited a change to the parser/scanner, with r27612.
For the file you sent me by mail, this is about 8x faster on my machine. Let me know what you get. I'll test the attached file in a moment.

(In reply to comment #2) > I've commited a change to the parser/scanner, with r27612. > > For the file you sent me by mail, this is about 8x faster on my machine. Let me > know what you get.
It is certainly way faster! It still takes the better part of a minute, though. What is it about this particular data that is so slow to parse? Is there a way I can reorganize the file so that parsing would be faster?
> I'll test the attached file in a moment.
It's the same as what I sent you.
Derrell

(In reply to comment #3) > It is certainly way faster! It still takes the better part of a minute, though. > What is it about this particular data that is so slow to parse? Is there a way > I can reorganize the file so that parsing would be faster?
I dunno. One factor is probably sheer size. The file is about 1MB. The biggest files in the framework are about 50K. Your file produces way above 16,000 tokens (qx.Class produces below 10,000), so that's just a lot of data for the parser to digest. I'll try and do some profiling. You could just try and split your mixin across e.g. 5 different mixins, see how that goes. Another option would be to keep Json-style data out of class code, and have it in dedicated .json files and load it from the app. That way you would avoid costly JS parsing, and get away with cheap (hopefully) Json parsing.

I profiled compiling your code. Most of the time is spent in the lowest scanner level, where the text is broken up into elementary tokens. Strange thing is: None of the code that is actually used to produce the tokens takes much time (according to the profiler), so all that is left is the Python built-in "yield" but it's hard to believe it should consume the vast majority of the run time. I'm a bit stumped on this...

Turns out that there was another culprit in the code: creating (large) slices of an (already large) string. Found a way to avoid the slicing, which improves performance again on my machine (Kudos to the folks on StackOverflow for both). Please re-test.
With r27616.

(In reply to comment #6) > Turns out that there was another culprit in the code
Wow! There sure was! The entire process of resolving dependencies is way faster now, and that file that was taking five minutes, originally, to be processed is now processed effectively immediately. Nice work!!!
Derrell

(In reply to comment #7) > Wow! There sure was! The entire process of resolving dependencies is way faster > now, and that file that was taking five minutes, originally, to be processed is > now processed effectively immediately. Nice work!!!
:-)) It's really just the parsing that is faster. But dependency analysis of course needs parsed code, and if you have multiple big files, that will benefit dep. analysis too. If most of your files are around 50K I doubt you will see much speed-up. But it was good to get that sorted out for big files. - Case closed?
Closed all bugs already shipped with a release.
